Package: xtop
Version: 0.47.3-1
Section: admin
Priority: optional
Architecture: amd64
Depends: libc6
Recommends: postgresql, journalctl
Installed-Size: 37740
Maintainer: Farhan Tahir <farhan.003@gmail.com>
Homepage: https://github.com/ftahirops/xtop
Description: Incident-first root-cause analysis console for Linux
 v0.47.3 hardens the docroot web-shell scanner against false
 positives on legitimate Unicode-handling libraries.
 .
 Obfuscation heuristics tightened — bare hex/chr/base64 patterns
 no longer fire alone:
   - "\x?? many escapes" now requires a runtime code-exec sink
     (eval/assert/gzinflate/gzuncompress/create_function) in the
     same file. Charset / entity-table libraries that legitimately
     use hundreds of \x?? escapes (SimplePie, mbstring polyfills)
     are silent.
   - chr() runs and long base64 blobs both require co-occurring
     dynamic-exec calls.
 .
 Path-based skip list extended with WP-core + common-framework
 subtrees that ship binary-encoding tables:
   SimplePie, Requests, PHPMailer, IXR, random_compat,
   sodium_compat, symfony, masterminds, guzzlehttp, psr, react
 .
 The direct shell signatures (eval/exec/system/shell_exec on
 user input, FilesMan/WSO/b374k/c99/r57 brand strings,
 web-shell extension tricks like .tkn / .php.png) remain at full
 sensitivity — no detection coverage was reduced.
 .
 Verified clean on 22-site Plesk + 18-site aaPanel with
 `xtop phpfpm --deep-scan` forced (was 2 false-positives in
 v0.47.2 from SimplePie + Misc.php; now zero).
